article.headline: Mystics' losing streak now at 11
article.story:
WASHINGTON (AP) -- Los Angeles Sparks coach Michael Cooper
couldn't help but be impressed with his top sharp shooter, but it
didn't stop there.

"Tamecka Dixon, what a player," he exclaimed.

Dixon had a career-high 28 points, and the Sparks beat
Washington 97-91 Wednesday night as the Mystics tied a franchise
record with their 11th straight defeat.

Dixon made 11 of 14 shots and was 5-for-5 from the free-throw
line as Los Angeles (15-3) increased its lead in the WNBA's Western
Conference to 4{ games over idle Houston.

Still, it was no breeze for the Sparks, who didn't win just
because Dixon had a superb performance.

"Again we took another team's great shot, and we responded
well," Cooper said. "Obviously we're not a one-player team with
the way we have people who can step up, but tonight she did a great
job."

The Sparks also got 18 points from Lisa Leslie, 16 apiece from
Mwadi Mabika and DeLisha Milton, and 15 from Nikki Teasley while
making 32 of 56 shots for a .571 percentage in the best offensive
showing of the season.

The Mystics, last in the Eastern Conference with the worst
record in the league, fell to 2-14 despite 27 points from Chamique
Holdsclaw to match her season high.

Washington also got 19 points from Stacey Dales-Schuman and 15
from Coco Miller, but lost to Los Angeles for the sixth straight
time. Still, Holdsclaw, who added eight rebounds, was not
disappointed.

"This is the type of effort we have to carry every night," she
said. "People around the league can't believe that we have this
record as much as we can't believe it. We're in games, and that's
the frustrating part.

"But I'm excited because this was our best game. We didn't back
down from the defending champs. LA is a great team; they're
athletic across the board, but we didn't back down."

The Mystics went on an 11-2 run to get within 78-71 on
Dales-Schuman's 3-pointer with 5:30 remaining, but that was as
close as they would get until Keisha Brown's 3-pointer with 6.3
seconds left.

Consecutive baskets by Dixon capped a 6-0 run to give the Sparks
a 23-17 lead with 8:30 remaining in the first half. After Holdsclaw
scored, Dixon added four more points to give the Sparks a 27-19
lead with 8:30 left in the half.

Both teams survived a scare when Leslie and Holdsclaw collided
and hit the floor in the opening two minutes, but neither was
seriously injured.

Leslie also had a season-high five blocks as the Sparks improved
to a league-best 10-1 on the road.

"Before, the bullseye was on our backs, trying to get the
back-to-back (championships), and now it's on our foreheads," said
Leslie, who also had nine rebounds. "We can never get complacent,
regardless of what the other team's record is.

"We know that we're going to get their best. That's just the
way it is when the Sparks are in the house, and that's why we have
to stay focused."
